-- в”Ђв”Ђ Nextpoint в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Nextpoint is a cloud-based eDiscovery and litigation support platform that helps law firms and corporate legal teams manage document review, case organization, and trial preparation without per-gigabyte data fees.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Custom$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2001, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Chicago, Illinois, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Nextpoint Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Nextpoint review 2026: eDiscovery and litigation support features, per-user pricing model with no data fees, and how it compares to Relativity and Everlaw.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Nextpoint was founded in 2001 in Chicago, Illinois, and has built its business around cloud-based eDiscovery and litigation support software for law firms and corporate legal departments. The company's central positioning in a market historically defined by per-gigabyte storage and processing charges is that it does not charge customers based on the amount of data they upload: Nextpoint offers free, unlimited data upload, processing, hosting, OCR (optical character recognition), imaging, and productions, and instead prices its subscriptions purely on a per-user, per-seat basis. This means legal teams can add as much evidence, documents, and case data as needed without worrying about data volume driving up their bill, and Nextpoint also does not charge extra for co-counsel, outside experts, or other external collaborators who need access to a shared case. The platform's core functionality spans the full litigation lifecycle: cloud-based document review, technology-assisted review (TAR) and predictive coding to speed up large-scale review projects, case and matter management, trial presentation and exhibit preparation tools, and production/export workflows for delivering discovery materials to opposing counsel or regulators. Nextpoint targets law firms of all sizes as well as corporate legal departments that handle recurring litigation or regulatory matters and want predictable, seat-based costs rather than unpredictable data-volume billing. On pricing specifics, Nextpoint does not publish detailed rate cards on its public website, and third-party review and pricing-aggregator sites report a wide and inconsistent range of figures for per-user monthly costs, some citing figures as low as roughly $49 per user per month for a basic tier and others citing figures in the hundreds of dollars per user per month for higher tiers with more capacity or advanced features; because these figures vary significantly across sources and are not confirmed directly by Nextpoint, prospective buyers are best served by contacting Nextpoint's sales team directly for an accurate, current quote based on their specific use case, team size, and matter volume. Competitors in the eDiscovery and litigation support space include Relativity (one of the dominant enterprise eDiscovery platforms), Logikcull, Everlaw, and DISCO, several of which similarly offer cloud-hosted review platforms but differ in their pricing structures, some retaining per-gigabyte or hybrid pricing models rather than Nextpoint's per-user-only approach. Nextpoint's differentiation in the market rests primarily on this cost-predictability angle: for legal teams whose data volumes are large or unpredictable, a flat per-user subscription with no data fees can significantly reduce and simplify eDiscovery costs compared to platforms that bill by gigabyte processed and hosted.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5b84747d-9c0b-41c9-af25-ea0cdbd81392';

